---
import '../styles/tokens.css';
---

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Observations | OurOrigin</title>
    <!-- Google Fonts with display=swap as explicitly requested -->
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin>
    <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Cinzel:wght@400..900&family=Cormorant+Garamond:wght@300;400;500&family=DM+Mono:ital,wght@0,300;0,400;0,500&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
    <style>
        body, html {
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            background-color: var(--color-forest-deep);
            color: var(--color-warm-cream);
            height: 100%;
        }
        .page-container {
            max-width: 800px;
            margin: 0 auto;
            padding: 20vh 5vw;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            gap: 2rem;
        }
        h1 {
            font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
            font-size: 2.5rem;
            margin: 0 0 1rem 0;
            font-weight: 400;
        }
        .subtitle {
            font-family: 'DM Mono', monospace;
            font-size: 0.9rem;
            text-transform: uppercase;
            letter-spacing: 0.1em;
            opacity: 0.6;
            margin: 0 0 3rem 0;
        }
        .empty-state {
            font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
            font-size: 1.5rem;
            line-height: 1.6;
            opacity: 0.8;
            font-style: italic;
        }
        .nav-link {
            font-family: 'DM Mono', monospace;
            color: var(--color-warm-cream);
            text-decoration: none;
            text-transform: uppercase;
            letter-spacing: 0.1em;
            margin-top: 4rem;
            display: inline-block;
            border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(244, 241, 235, 0.3);
            padding-bottom: 0.2rem;
            transition: border-color 0.3s ease;
            align-self: flex-start;
        }
        .nav-link:hover {
            border-bottom-color: var(--color-warm-cream);
        }
        .fssai-footer {
            margin-top: auto;
            padding-top: 4rem;
            font-family: 'DM Mono', monospace;
            font-size: 0.75rem;
            color: var(--color-warm-cream);
            opacity: 0.4;
            text-align: left;
        }
        .observation {
            margin-bottom: 3rem;
            border-left: 1px solid rgba(244, 241, 235, 0.2);
            padding-left: 2rem;
        }
        .obs-title {
            font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
            font-size: 1.3rem;
            font-weight: 400;
            margin: 0 0 1rem 0;
            color: var(--color-gold);
        }
        .obs-body {
            font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
            font-size: 1.3rem;
            line-height: 1.6;
            margin: 0 0 1rem 0;
            opacity: 0.9;
        }
        .obs-meta {
            font-family: 'DM Mono', monospace;
            font-size: 0.8rem;
            text-transform: uppercase;
            letter-spacing: 0.05em;
            opacity: 0.5;
            margin: 0;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="page-container">
        <h1>Observations</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">Field notes, logs, and tracking</p>
        
        <div class="observation">
            <h2 class="obs-title">Observation 01: "The berry that turned black was never black"</h2>
            <p class="obs-body">Every batch of black pepper starts green. The colour change happens entirely after harvest, during sun-drying. Picked green, dried black. The colour you've associated with pepper your entire life is not the colour of the plant. It's the colour of what happens to the plant after it's picked. This is one of the oldest continuous misunderstandings in the kitchen.</p>
            <p class="obs-meta">Related: Forest Black Pepper — Wayanad & Nilgiris, 900–1,100m</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="observation">
            <h2 class="obs-title">Observation 02: "Cardamom grows in shade by preference, not by accident"</h2>
            <p class="obs-body">Most spice plants are planted in cleared, open ground. Cardamom is not. It grows under a canopy — deliberately left intact, because Elettaria cardamomum produces better pods when it receives filtered light rather than direct sun. The tall trees above a cardamom garden are not vestiges of forest that wasn't fully cleared. They are part of the cultivation. Shade is a production input, not an oversight.</p>
            <p class="obs-meta">Related: Cardamom — Idukki, 1,200m</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="observation">
            <h2 class="obs-title">Observation 03: "Mace and nutmeg come from the same tree"</h2>
            <p class="obs-body">Most people have bought both mace and nutmeg at some point. Most people do not know they come from the same plant — or more precisely, the same fruit. Myristica fragrans produces a fleshy outer fruit that splits when ripe to reveal a seed (nutmeg) wrapped in a lace-like red covering (mace). Both are harvested from the same tree, in the same moment, from the same fruit. The culinary world treats them as entirely separate spices. The tree doesn't make that distinction.</p>
            <p class="obs-meta">Related: Mace — Idukki, 1,200m</p>
        </div>
        
        <a href="/" class="nav-link">Return to the Matrix</a>
        
        <div class="fssai-footer">FSSAI Reg. No. 21326135000354</div>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
